Photo by @sinnaevephotos / Prior to leaving NYC for the holidays, I visited the Whitney Museum in order to see the Edward Hopper exhibition. Like many brilliant artists, Mr. Hopper was a master of finding the beauty in what most people would consider to be mundane. One aspect of his work that stood out to me was his voyeuristic, sidewalk perspective. As someone who has spent a fair amount of time over the past six years wandering the streets of New York City with a camera in their hands, this point of view has become familiar to me. 

The photograph you’re looking at, however, is neither New York City nor is it likely a place that Edward Hopper frequented; it is a sidewalk scene from a city closer to home known as Marquette, Michigan, that I photographed this past summer.  More specifically, this is Getz’s Clothiers, a family owned department store that has operated out of the same building in historic Downtown Marquette since 1900. To have been in business for over 120 years is a remarkable feat in itself, but it’s even more impressive when you consider the fact that department stores are shuttering at a rapid pace across the entire US. 

Both Edward Hopper and stores like Getz’s serve as reminders of a different time in America and connect us to the past. If you still need to do some last-minute holiday shopping, then I encourage you to shop local and support small businesses. It makes a difference.

This is the marriage certificate of Andrew G. Björn and Emma Nielson (spelled Nelson on the document). They were married on June 2nd, 1906, at 116 East 54th Street in Manhattan. 

Andrew Björn and Emma Nielson were my great-great-grandparents. When I look at this certificate, it’s a humbling reminder of how much those who came before me had to endure in order for me to exist. If you’re reading this, then this philosophical concept applies to you as well. There’s a purpose for our existence.

Photo by @sinnaevephotos / The Washington Mews’ cobblestone passageway is nestled between Fifth Avenue and University Place (just north of Washington Square Park). 

The mews (a row of stables) originally serviced horses from homes in the area, but were later converted into studios for “the area’s thriving art community.”

New York University has held the lease since 1949 and gradually converted the buildings into offices and faculty housing during that time.

Photo by @sinnaevephotos / Whitney Museum of American Art (@thewhitneymuseum) visual description: The painting, Untitled, 1969, is on a large, rectangular composition board about 6 feet wide by 4 feet tall. The surface is a rich blue that evokes the deep sea.

There are three images painted onto the canvas, visually dividing the painting into approximately three vertical sections. The painting is in the style of a scientific diagram, meant to measure accuracy and relay subject matter in great detail. Though these images are large and take up the majority of the blue backdrop, they are detailed enough to be inscrutable from more than a few feet away. The images--made up of fine white lines--are directly inspired by diagrams created by abolitionist activists in the late eighteenth century to relay the atrocities of the transatlantic slave trade and the inhuman conditions under which human cargo was transported from Africa to the West Indies and America. The straightforward, diorama-likestyle of this work contrasts starkly with the horror of the subject matter.

The middle image is of a plant with several leaves and three flowers; two in bloom and one bud. There is an inscription in small lettering beneath the plant that reads “Cotton Plants with Buds Gossypium Herbaceum ~ Latin”. The two images on either side are oval-like and span from nearly the top of the canvas to the bottom. There are measurements and dimensions noted within and along the shapes, making it clear they are the blueprint for something much larger. Along these lines are small, repeating, identical human figures, which leads us to understand the outlines as the cross-section of large ships. The delicately painted human bodies are lined up, efficiently shoulder to shoulder. On the left ship blueprint, the bodies span the vertical length of the ship in a single line. At times, there are gaps between the bodies and at other times they are unfinished, beginning with the head and shoulders before fading into the blue of the background. In the blueprint to the right, the bodies are confined to the middle portion of the ship and are neatly stacked three rows wide.

Malcolm Bailey
Untitled, 1969
1969

Photo by @sinnaevephotos / Last spring, I bought a piece of fabric from an African textile dealer for a shoot with my friend, David. This textured fabric is traditionally used by women to carry their babies, but we thought it would be interesting to experiment with styling it in a nontraditional way.

David and I woke up before the sunrise and made our way out to a salt marsh on the outskirts of NYC that I was familiar with because I had been photographed there for a project several years prior.

When we arrived, David and I carried our bags through the wide-open fields until we reached a patch of marsh grass near the water. There came a moment when my vision, which, up to this point was purely conceptual, suddenly became practical after what can only be described as a rush of creative inspiration. As strange as this may sound, I saw this image of David before I took the actual photograph in a similar way to how a painter might see the painting before they even pick up their paintbrush.

Knowing what you want is only a piece of the puzzle; figuring out how to get what you want presents an entirely different set of challenges. I wrapped the fabric around David's neck like a scarf, and had him bring his hair to the side so it wrapped in the same direction as the fabric, lowered my aperture in order to blur the grass in the background, and asked David to squat down and lean slightly forward.

The final stage of bringing this vision to life required a bit of luck. It was a partially cloudy day, which I typically love because the clouds act as a natural diffuser and soften the light. However, when the sun breaks through the clouds, you're suddenly left dealing with hard light and harsh shadows. Unfortunately, the transition between these two conditions was happening in rapid succession throughout the day. To further complicate matters, we needed a gust of wind to blow the grass in a specific direction in order to not only frame David's face, but also follow the flow of his hair and scarf. Fortunately for us, it was our lucky day.

Photo by @sinnaevephotos / "When I admire the wonders of a sunset or the beauty of the moon, my soul expands in the worship of the creator." —Mahatma Gandhi

Photo by @hadar_pitchon / "You and I, and all of life, we were all born out of the death of a star, millions of billions of years ago. A star that lived long and then, before its death, burned at its brightest, its fiercest - an enflaming supernova. 

But when it died, it did not cease to exist; instead everything it was made of became part of the universe once again, and everything that is part of the universe will once more become part of us.

So do not miss me, because I do not die; I transform - into the wind in the tops of the trees, the wave on the ocean, the pebbles under your foot, the dust on your bookshelves, the midnight sky.

Wherever you look, I will be there."

—Rowan Coleman, "We Are All Made of Stars”
